body:
IMO this fixed that:

```
x11_monitor.c:

// Convert RandR mode info to GLFW video mode
static GLFWvidmode vidmodeFromModeInfo(const XRRModeInfo* mi, const XRRCrtcInfo* ci)
{
    GLFWvidmode mode;

    // Test if the monitor rotation is +/- 90 degree.
    if (ci->rotation == RR_Rotate_90 || ci->rotation == RR_Rotate_270) {
        // swap w/h
        mode.width = mi->height;
        mode.height = mi->width;
    } else {
        mode.width = mi->width;
        mode.height = mi->height;
    }
    mode.refreshRate = calculateRefreshRate(mi);

    _glfwSplitBPP(DefaultDepth(_glfw.x11.display, _glfw.x11.screen),
        &mode.redBits, &mode.greenBits, &mode.blueBits);

    return mode;
}
```

I encountered this as well using the Oculus Rift DK2.  It's actually seen by the computer as a 1080x1920 screen and normal use requires that it be rotated 90 degrees counterclockwise.  The Rift also reports an odd resolution of 1080x940 (or something close to that).  When telling glfw to create a full screen window of 1920x1080 it becomes confused and switches to the 1080x940 mode.

I tracked this down to logic in _glfwSetVideoMode in x11_monitor.c:

Specifically this:

```
        sizeDiff = (mi->width - desired->width) *
                   (mi->width - desired->width) +
                   (mi->height - desired->height) *
                   (mi->height - desired->height);
```

even though the code that sets the mode later in `XRRSetCrtcConfig` actually retains the orientation, the sizeDiff calculations are thrown off because they don't respect to rotation.  I was able to correct the issue with the following change:

```
        unsigned int modeWidth = mi->width;
        unsigned int modeHeight = mi->height;
        if (ci->rotation == RR_Rotate_90 || ci->rotation == RR_Rotate_270) {
          modeWidth = mi->height;
          modeHeight = mi->width;
        }
        sizeDiff = (modeWidth - desired->width) *
                   (modeWidth - desired->width) +
                   (modeHeight - desired->height) *
                   (modeHeight - desired->height);
```
